<div class="container">
    <h1 class="text-center">What is a Database?</h1>

    <div class="beginner-note">
        <div class="beginner-note-icon">
            <i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i>
        </div>
        <div class="beginner-note-content">
            <h4>Important Note for Beginners</h4>
            <p><strong>Don't worry if some concepts seem complicated at first!</strong> The goal of this chapter is to understand the <strong>big picture</strong> - what databases are and why we use them.</p>
            <p>You <strong>don't need to memorize</strong> every technical detail. Focus on understanding:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>The concept:</strong> What is a database and what does it do?</li>
                <li><strong>The why:</strong> Why do we need databases instead of simple files?</li>
                <li><strong>The basic structure:</strong> How is data organized in a database?</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Best part:</strong> As a C# developer, you'll use <strong>C# code</strong> to work with databases, not complicated database languages! We'll show you examples along the way.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="intro-section">
        <p>A <strong>database</strong> is like a digital filing cabinet where you can store and organize information. Think of it as an organized collection of data that you can access, manage, and update easily.</p>
        
        <div class="analogy-box">
            <h3>Simple Analogy: A Library</h3>
            <p>Imagine a library:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Books</strong> = Your data (information)</li>
                <li><strong>Shelves</strong> = Tables in a database</li>
                <li><strong>Library catalog system</strong> = Database management system</li>
                <li><strong>Librarian</strong> = Database software that helps you find what you need</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Without organization, finding a specific book would take hours. With a system, you find it in seconds!</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">Why Do We Need Databases?</h2>
    
    <div class="reasons-container">
        <div class="reason-card">
            <h4>1. Organized Storage</h4>
            <p>Instead of having information scattered in different files (like text files, Excel sheets), databases keep everything in one organized place.</p>
            <div class="example">
                <p><strong>Example:</strong> Storing student information:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><span style="color: #dc3545;">Without database:</span> student1.txt, student2.txt, grades.xlsx, attendance.csv...</li>
                    <li><span style="color: #198754;">With database:</span> One organized system with all student data together</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="reason-card">
            <h4>2. Easy to Find Information</h4>
            <p>Databases let you quickly find specific information without looking through everything manually.</p>
            <div class="example">
                <p><strong>Example:</strong> Finding all students with grade "A":</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><span style="color: #dc3545;">Manual search:</span> Open each student file, check grade</li>
                    <li><span style="color: #198754;">Database search:</span> One simple command finds all "A" students instantly</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="reason-card">
            <h4>3. Multiple People Can Use It</h4>
            <p>Many users can access the same database at the same time without problems.</p>
            <div class="example">
                <p><strong>Example:</strong> School system:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Teachers add grades</li>
                    <li>Students check their grades</li>
                    <li>Administrators view reports</li>
                    <li>All happening at the same time!</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="reason-card">
            <h4>4. Keeps Data Safe</h4>
            <p>Databases have built-in protection and backup features.</p>
            <div class="example">
                <p><strong>Example:</strong> What if your computer crashes?</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><span style="color: #dc3545;">Text files:</span> Data might be lost forever</li>
                    <li><span style="color: #198754;">Database:</span> Automatic backups keep your data safe</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">Basic Database Concepts (Simple Version)</h2>

    <div class="concepts-container">
        <div class="concept-box">
            <h4>Table</h4>
            <p>A table is like a spreadsheet where you store related information. Each table has a specific purpose.</p>
            <div class="code-container">
                <div class="code-header">Example: Students Table</div>
                <div class="code-content">
<pre>
┌─────────┬──────────┬──────┬─────────┐
│ Student │   Name   │ Age  │  Grade  │
├─────────┼──────────┼──────┼─────────┤
│    1    │  Alice   │  20  │    A    │
│    2    │   Bob    │  21  │    B    │
│    3    │ Charlie  │  19  │    A    │
│    4    │  Diana   │  22  │    C    │
└─────────┴──────────┴──────┴─────────┘

This table stores basic student information.
Each row = One student
Each column = Type of information (Name, Age, Grade)
</pre>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h4>Record (or Row)</h4>
            <p>A single entry in a table. In the example above, each student is one record.</p>
            <div class="example">
                <p><strong>Record example:</strong> Alice's information (Student: 1, Name: Alice, Age: 20, Grade: A) is one complete record.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h4>Field (or Column)</h4>
            <p>A specific piece of information in a table. Each column represents one type of data.</p>
            <div class="example">
                <p><strong>Field examples:</strong> "Name" column, "Age" column, "Grade" column</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-box">
            <h4>Primary Key</h4>
            <p>A unique identifier for each record. Like a student ID number - no two students have the same ID.</p>
            <div class="example">
                <p><strong>Example:</strong> Student numbers (1, 2, 3, 4) are primary keys. They uniquely identify each student.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">Real-World Examples You Use Every Day</h2>

    <div class="real-world-examples">
        <div class="example-item">
            <h4>Social Media (Facebook, Instagram)</h4>
            <p><strong>What's stored:</strong> Your profile, posts, friends, messages, likes</p>
            <p><strong>Database role:</strong> Keeps track of who's friends with whom, shows your feed, stores your photos</p>
        </div>

        <div class="example-item">
            <h4>Online Shopping (Amazon, eBay)</h4>
            <p><strong>What's stored:</strong> Products, prices, your cart, order history, reviews</p>
            <p><strong>Database role:</strong> Shows you products, remembers what you looked at, processes your orders</p>
        </div>

        <div class="example-item">
            <h4>Email (Gmail, Outlook)</h4>
            <p><strong>What's stored:</strong> Your emails, contacts, sent items, folders</p>
            <p><strong>Database role:</strong> Keeps your emails organized, lets you search, stores attachments</p>
        </div>

        <div class="example-item">
            <h4>Music Streaming (Spotify, Apple Music)</h4>
            <p><strong>What's stored:</strong> Songs, playlists, your favorites, listening history</p>
            <p><strong>Database role:</strong> Creates your playlists, suggests new music, remembers what you like</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">Good News for Beginners</h2>

    <div class="good-news-box">
        <h3>You Don't Need to Learn SQL (Yet)!</h3>
        <p>In traditional database courses, you'd need to learn SQL (Structured Query Language) - a special language for talking to databases.</p>
        
        <div class="code-container">
            <div class="code-header">Traditional SQL Example (Don't worry about this!)</div>
            <div class="code-content">
<pre>
<span style="color: #198754;">-- SQL code to get all students with grade 'A'</span>
SELECT Name, Age 
FROM Students 
WHERE Grade = 'A';

<span style="color: #198754;">-- SQL code to add a new student</span>
INSERT INTO Students (Name, Age, Grade) 
VALUES ('Emma', 20, 'B');
</pre>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="csharp-advantage">
            <h4>C# Does It for You!</h4>
            <p>With C# and .NET, you can work with databases using regular C# code! The framework translates your C# code into SQL automatically.</p>
            
            <div class="code-container">
                <div class="code-header">C# Way (Much Easier!)</div>
                <div class="code-content">
<pre>
<span style="color: #198754;">// Get all students with grade 'A' - Using C#!</span>
var topStudents = dbContext.Students
    .Where(s => s.Grade == "A")
    .ToList();

<span style="color: #198754;">// Add a new student - Using C#!</span>
var newStudent = new Student 
{
    Name = "Emma",
    Age = 20,
    Grade = "B"
};
dbContext.Students.Add(newStudent);
dbContext.SaveChanges();
</pre>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <p><strong>See? You're using familiar C# code, not a new language!</strong> The database work happens behind the scenes.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">What You'll Learn in This Chapter</h2>

    <div class="learning-goals">
        <div class="goal">
            <h4>1. Understanding Concepts</h4>
            <p>Learn what databases are and why we use them (no coding yet!)</p>
        </div>

        <div class="goal">
            <h4>2. Database Types</h4>
            <p>See different kinds of databases and when to use each</p>
        </div>

        <div class="goal">
            <h4>3. Relationships</h4>
            <p>Learn how data connects (like how students connect to courses)</p>
        </div>

    </div>

    <div class="beginner-tip">
        <h3>Beginner Tip</h3>
        <p><strong>Don't worry about SQL commands!</strong> Focus on understanding:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>What data goes where</li>
            <li>How different pieces of information connect</li>
            <li>How to get data when you need it</li>
        </ul>
        <p>You'll write C# code, and the database magic happens automatically!</p>
    </div>

